ce:section.ce:para:
Brewery waste yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) from Tsingtao beer production, was kindly donated by Tsingtao Brewery Co. Ltd. (Qingdao, China). Yeast samples were first washed in distilled water to remove beer residue. Then, they were dried in a freeze drier (Freezezone 4.5, Labconoco, USA) under a pressure lower than 0.003 mBar at −45 °C for 48 h. The lyophilized yeast samples were then ground into powders, vacuumed packed and stored at -18 °C. The surface area and pore volume of yeast particles were determined by the N2-BET method in a surface area and porosimetry analyzer (ASAP 2020, Micromeritics, Norcross, USA), being 0.942 m2/g and 0.0018 m2/g, respectively. The solid density measured by toluene displacement method [27] was found to be 0.92 g/cm3. Furthermore, the void fraction value (εp
                        ) of yeast was close to zero (0.0017), which was measured using the method of Dotto et al. [23]. The extremely low εp
                         value indicated that yeast samples were solid particles instead of porous particles.

The influences of different operating parameters, including the AED level, temperature and biosorption time on the quantity of phenolics adsorbed on yeast cells were studied. For this purpose, a three-layered feed-forward ANN model with 8 neurons in the hidden layer (Fig. 2
                        ) was constructed to build a quantitative relationship between these parameters and yeast biosorption capacity. The “tansig” and “purelin” functions were used in the hidden and output layers, respectively. Applications of these two transfer functions led to a considerably higher predictive accuracy after the training of ANN models with different architectures. Meanwhile, the weight and bias values corresponding to the neurons in the hidden and output layers are given in Supplementary Table 1. Furthermore, the performance of the constructed ANN model for prediction is also presented in Fig. 2. It can be seen that for both the training and cross-validation datasets, this ANN model was characterized by a high R
                        2 value (approaching 1) and low RMSE and AAD values. Therefore, the constructed ANN model was robust enough to predict the quantity of phenolics adsorbed by brewery waste yeast as a function of the AED level, temperature and biosorption time within the studied experimental range. In general, ANN, by virtue of nonlinear mapping ability, is a more advanced method to clarify the effects of various parameters on the target response than the widely used response surface methodology [46].
